<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Financing for Krasnoyarsk aluminium plant begun
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Aluminium Pechiney said yesterday that it has started work on the financing
of an estimated USDollars 400-Dollars 500m project to modernise the Russian
Krasnoyarsk aluminium plant, reports Reuters from Paris.
Its chairman, Mr Bernard Legrand, said the funds would be used to construct
an initial production line of 250,000 tonnes a year.
Annual output capacity at Krasnoyarsk would eventually be brought back up to
its existing capacity of some 800,000 tonnes, which would require even more
funding, he said.
Aluminium Pechiney will work on the financing project with investment bank
Morgan Grenfell as financial adviser and Bechtel Corp of the US.
Mr Legrand said he had a meeting on Tuesday with Russian prime minister
Victor Chernomyrdin, who confirmed his willingness to proceed quickly with
the first step of the Krasnoyarsk project.
The upgrading of Krasnoyarsk wouldl be followed by modernisation of a second
plant at Bratsk, which also has a current capacity of some 800,000, said Mr
Legrand.
The Krasnoyarsk and Bratsk plants are each now producing about 700,000
tonnes a year.
The modernisation plan is in line with the conclusions of the Canberra
aluminium conference on July 20-21, which stressed the need to integrate
Russian producers into world markets, he said.
Legrand said Pechiney had been invited a year ago by the Russian Committee
on Metallurgy to conduct a study on the modernisation of three Russian
smelting facilities at Krasnoyarsk, Bratsk and Novokuznetsk. Novokuznetsk
has an existing capacity of 300,000 to 400,000 tonnes.
An evaluation committee aproved the Pechiney report last May and selected
Pechiney to work on the modernisation of Bratsk and Krasnoyarsk.
Legrand said he expects work on Krasnoyarsk to start within two years. The
modernisation of Bratsk is expected to follow. Initial output for Bratsk
will also be 250,000 tonnes per year, with capacity eventually rising back
up to 800,000 tonnes.
Legrand said the whole modernisation project for Krasnoyarsk and Bratsk
could take five to 10 years.
</TEXT>
