<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries make solid gains after rally by
dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A rally by the dollar helped US Treasury bonds post solid gains yesterday
despite initial jitters over an ambiguous economic reading.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  9/16 higher
at 84 23/32 , with the yield slipping to 7.55 per cent. At the short end,
the two-year note was up  1/16 at 99 27/32 , to yield 6.193 per cent.
Bonds across the spectrum came under early pressure after the Labor
Department reported that initial claims for unemployment benefit last week
fell by 59,000 to 331,000, the lowest since March 26.
Analysts, however, attributed the decline to technical factors and
discounted the raw data as an accurate indication of the economy's strength.
The benign interpretation allowed Treasuries to climb back into positive
territory, although the approach of today's preliminary estimate of
second-quarter gross domestic product held bonds in check during the
morning.
Today's report should provide a clue to the timing of the Federal Reserve's
next move to lift short-term interest rates. Economists were predicting
second-quarter growth of 3.9 per cent, up from 3.4 per cent in the first
three months of the year. A reading that exceeds the consensus forecast
could cause prices to tumble.
As traders sought to square their positions ahead of the data, the dollar
staged an impressive afternoon rally in the foreign exchange markets. The
development eased the way for dealers seeking to distribute new two-year and
five-year notes auctioned by the Treasury earlier in the week, bringing a
measure of confidence to the market going into the GDP announcement.
In the absence of significant fundamental news, European government bonds
spent another day drifting sideways on low volume. However, volatility
remained high due to thin market conditions.
Gilts had another roller-coaster session: falling at the opening in the
aftermath of Wednesday's sell-off, recovering on investor buying and easing
back in late trade on worries about a rise in UK interest rates. The
September long gilt futures contract closed at 101 9/32 , up  5/32 on the
day.
Continuing worries about the possibility of an imminent rate increase, which
pushed three-month rates to their year's high yesterday, continued to weigh
on the market.
'Most people have been expecting rates to rise eventually, but now there's
increasing talk that we'll see a pre-emptive rate hike sooner than
expected,' said a senior gilt trader.
Nervousness ahead of today's second-quarter US GDP data also overhung the
market. 'Going into the data, people aren't willing to take any sizeable
positions either way,' said Mr Ifty Islam of Merrill Lynch.
Still, traders reported some investor buying of medium and long-dated stock,
which helped gilts recoup their losses during the day. Switching into gilts
from neighbouring markets was also reported, helping gilts' 10-year yield
spread over bunds to narrow to around 183 basis points from Wednesday's high
of 195 basis points.
Trading in the German bond market was technical and futures-driven, with
retail investors said to be sidelined. The late breach of key support levels
on the September bund future gave scope for further falls in the contract
and, according to Mr Peter Kerger, head of futures and options at NatWest
Markets in Frankfurt, it could test 92.20 in the coming days. However, he
said he does not expect it to revisit its recent low of just below 90.00.
The contract ended at 92.82 on Germany's DTB, down 0.48 points on the day.
French bonds fell in line with bunds, ignoring the Bank of France's widely
expected 10 basis point cut in its intervention rate to 5 per cent. The
September notional bond contract on Matif ended the day at 116.84, down 0.34
points on the day.
Italian bonds took a breather after the recent sell-off, closing only
slightly weaker. However, sentiment remains weak given the fragile political
background, and the market is expected to remain volatile as the corruption
probe continues into Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi's holding company
Fininvest.
</TEXT>
