<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / International Company News: US carriers confirm tentative
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Delta and Continental, two leading US airlines, yesterday provided further
evidence of the industry's tentative recovery by posting improved
second-quarter operating results.
Delta, the country's third biggest carrier, announced a 61 per cent surge in
operating income to Dollars 92.3m, excluding a Dollars 413.7m pre-tax charge
related to a restructuring programme announced last April.
The result reflects a 1.5 per cent gain in operating revenues to Dollars
3.18m, and a 4 per cent upturn in operating revenue in terms of available
passenger seats. The higher return more than offset a slight increase in
operating expenses to Dollars 3.09bn.
Net income, excluding the provision, was marginally ahead at Dollars 10.8m,
against Dollars 7.2m in the second three months of 1993. However, the bottom
line was a loss of 33 cents a share, against a deficit of 41 cents in the
year-earlier period.
In spite of the progress, Mr Ronald Allen, Delta's chairman, said the
airline was still a long way from achieving its goal of sustained
profitability.
Meanwhile, Continental, the Texas-based carrier which emerged form its
second bankruptcy in April 1993, narrowed its operating loss to Dollars 1.5m
on revenues of Dollars 1.4bn. The result represents a considerable
improvement on the 1993 quarter, when the airline posted an operating
deficit of Dollars 62m on Dollars 1.45bn in revenues.
Operating expenses were sharply lower at Dollars 1.39bn, against Dollars
1.51bn in the corresponding period of 1993.
The net loss for the most recent quarter was Dollars 48.9m, or Dollars 1.97
a share. The previous year's figures are not comparable because the company
was recapitalised when it emerged from Chapter 11.
PWA, parent of Canadian Airlines International, posted a small profit for
the June quarter, writes Robert Gibbens in Montreal. Second-quarter
operating income was CDollars 31.6m (USDollars 22m) against a CDollars 16.7m
loss a year earlier. Net profit was CDollars 1.5m, against a loss of
CDollars 131m last time which included a CDollars 86m restructuring expense.
Revenues were CDollars 727m, up 6.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
