<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Sainsbury takes store wars into a new phase: Why Wm Low has
attracted the giants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Sainsbury yesterday ushered in a new era at the UK's largest food
retailer with his 305p-a-share rival bid to Tesco's agreed 225p offer for Wm
Low.
Chairman since the start of last year, he did what none of his predecessors
had done: launched a hostile bid. It is true that because Wm Low's board had
already endorsed another offer, Sainsbury's bid is not strictly 'hostile',
but the company is at least entering a contest.
The Columbia Business School-educated chairman also took competition between
the biggest food retailers into a new phase, as the struggles over new sites
in the early 1990s and recent price skirmishing gave way to a battle for
control of a smaller player.
He may have been motivated partly by pique that Wm Low had agreed Tesco's
offer without speaking to Sainsbury - especially since it approached the
Scottish company last year only to be told Low was determined to remain
independent. Sainsbury certainly did not want to see Tesco walk off with it
at a bargain price.
But Sainsbury's bid of 305p per ordinary share and 143p per convertible
preference share - valuing the company at Pounds 210m compared with Tesco's
Pounds 154m - is seen as evidence that Sainsbury genuinely wants Wm Low.
'The 305p price is higher than expected, and clearly designed to make Tesco
think long and hard about whether to respond,' said Mr Bill Myers, food
retailing analyst at Yamaichi.
The main attraction of Wm Low to Sainsbury, as to Tesco, is the chance to
buy market share quickly and relatively cheaply in Scotland - one of the
last areas of the UK not overrun by grocery superstores. Sainsbury says the
acquisition would increase its Scottish market share from 3 per cent to 10
per cent, and its UK share from 11.4 to 12 per cent.
Sainsbury has only four stores in Scotland. Its ambitions there have been
hampered by intense competition for sites and struggles with local
authorities over planning permission.
Although many Wm Low supermarkets are small, the acquisition would give
Sainsbury 57 stores for the cost of building and opening 12 superstores.
Sainsbury says it has no plans to sell any of the stores, but admits rivals
have expressed interest and 'recognises that some of Wm Low's smaller stores
may be of greater interest to other operators'.
It believes it can make Wm Low's assets work harder and is proposing Pounds
40m investment in the stores - Pounds 5m more than Tesco.
Overheads would be cut by closing Wm Low's head office, and economies of
scale exploited by bringing the stores into Sainsbury's supply and
distribution network.
It would refurbish the stores, reduce prices and widen the range by selling
its own-label products. Some superstores would be extended and petrol
stations added.
Sainsbury believes it can raise the Scottish stores' performance towards
that of the rest of its chain, and says it is best placed to unlock their
potential as its performance ratios lead the industry. Sainsbury's weekly
sales per square foot of Pounds 18.70 are twice those of Wm Low's Pounds
9.60, and well above Tesco's Pounds 15.20. Annual profits per square foot,
at Pounds 85.50, are three times Wm Low's Pounds 27.60, and 45 per cent
above Tesco's Pounds 59.
Analysts believe Sainsbury could achieve a 50 per cent increase in Wm Low's
operating profits to about Pounds 27m in the medium term.
The acquisition would also give Sainsbury a much-needed Scottish
distribution depot. Its Scottish stores are presently supplied by trucks
from north-east England and Lancashire.
Some analysts had suggested Sainsbury might not bid for Wm Low but save its
money for a bigger acquisition in the US. However, with a successful
takeover of Wm Low projected to increase year-end gearing from 20 per cent
to only 27 per cent, it is clear Sainsbury still has scope for acquisitions
elsewhere.
Mr Sainsbury repeated yesterday that the group would investigate any
opportunities to add to its Shaws chain in the US, but this was a 'statement
of strategy, not an indication we are about to pounce on something'.
However, whether Sainsbury or Tesco eventually triumphs in the battle for Wm
Low, some suggest it could open the door to other bids for UK food
retailers.
Mr Jeremy Alun-Jones, analyst at Lehman Brothers, believes the most
significant comment came from Tesco, which said the acquisition of Wm Low
would enable it to expand its market share 'without increasing total
industry floorspace'.
If the biggest players start to believe the market is saturated and
expansion should not add to industry capacity, smaller companies such as
Iceland, Gateway, the co-operative societies, or even Wm Morrison could
become targets.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
