<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Pensions guide delayed by SIB
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Full guidance on how to review the personal pensions sold to people
transferring from, or opting out of, occupational schemes will not be
available until October, the Securities and Investments Board, the chief
City regulator, said yesterday.
SIB had intended to publish by the end of this month the guidelines for life
companies and financial advisers on how to review their cases and compensate
customers who had suffered from poor advice to take a transfer or opt out.
SIB's plan was announced last December after public concern about possible
mis-selling of personal pensions was fuelled by a pilot study showing a
widespread disregard of regulatory requirements.
Announcing the delay, SIB said that the work was well-advanced but that it
wanted to assess over the summer how workable the approach which had been
developed would be. It decided against publishing any interim guidance in
case this caused confusion.
While the regulator has made progress with devising compensation
arrangements, several sensitive issues that concern the relative
responsibilities of life companies and of independent financial advisers
have not yet been resolved.
Nor has it yet been decided whether to publish the results of the two
research projects that were commissioned by SIB on the extent and range of
pensions business.
SIB insisted yesterday that the delay did not undermine the urgency with
which remedying past mistakes was being tackled.
It published guidelines in May on how life companies and advisers should go
about identifying cases which should be reviewed as a priority, for example
where the pension-holder had already retired.
</TEXT>
