<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Ford launches used-car factory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford yesterday opened what it said was the world's first used-car factory,
employing more than 200 on a 15-acre facility at Tilbury, Essex.
The 'Ford Direct' plant, a joint venture between Ford, Silcock Express, the
logistics group, and the Royal Automobile Club, has the capacity to
recondition and prepare as many as 1,500 used cars a week for resale by
Ford's network of franchised dealers.
The venture is believed to be the first used-car retailing scheme in which
the manufacturer takes direct responsibility for preparing vehicles for sale
and providing warranties for them.
The decision to go ahead with the project was taken in response to research
by Ford over nearly two years which showed motorists to be 'deeply cynical'
about the integrity of the retail motor trade.
More than 13,000 Ford cars up to a year old and with a total showroom value
of Pounds 105m have been refurbished and sold since the Ford Direct scheme,
selling used cars with essentially new-car warranties and with a 30-day
exchange option, started earlier this year.
The cars have until now been prepared at four small regional centres.
Ford is starting a pilot project in Scotland under which cars up to three
years old will be brought within the scheme. In the Scottish scheme, the
cars will be refurbished by dealers and passed to RAC engineers for
independent assessment.
About Pounds 5m has been spent on the Tilbury plant, which is being operated
by Silcock Express on Ford's behalf, using Ford-trained personnel. Cars less
than a year old are collected from Ford and its main fleet customers and
taken to one of five Silcock regional distribution centres for shipment to
Tilbury.
At the plant cars are labelled with a bar code allowing them to be tracked
through all stages of preparation. They then transfer to an inspection bay,
where 20 RAC engineers assess the vehicles and list refurbishment
requirements.
Silcock Express, a subsidiary of the Tibbett and Britten logistics group, is
the UK's biggest new-car distribution contractor, handling about 1.5m cars
last year. Most of Ford's rivals run their own dealer-based
'manufacturer-approved' used-car retailing schemes, such as Vauxhall's
Network Q operation, and dismissed Ford's initiative as a 'hyped-up'
variation of their own schemes.
Ford insisted, however, that its scheme eliminates the three most serious
concerns voiced by consumers about other operations: that dealer-based
'independent' pre-sale checks and tests are neither properly independent nor
rigorous; that warranties offered are not comprehensive enough; and that too
often dealers try not to honour them.
</TEXT>
