FT  29 JUL 94 / NHS managers face large job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thousands of jobs including senior Civil Service posts will disappear under
proposals to streamline the central management of the National Health
Service announced yesterday.
Strict upper limits on the number of staff employed in regional
administration will lead to the abolition of more than half the posts in
regional health authorities.
The regions have already been through one recent job-reduction exercise,
which resulted in the number of people working in them being cut to 2,600
from 3,900 last year. Under yesterday's proposals a further 1,500 posts will
go.
In addition, 2,300 employees in the Department of Health's headquarters in
London and the 1,000 in the Leeds-based NHS executive were warned yesterday
that there would be 'substantial' cuts.
The reductions are likely to begin in the autumn. The government said it
hoped to avoid compulsory redundancies.
The proposed losses are the result of a review of the NHS's central
management requirements now that much decision-making has been devolved to
local level. Ministers have been under pressure to stem the growth in
mana-gerial and administrative posts.
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, said yesterday that he was taking similar
steps to improve NHS efficiency in Wales. He plans to divert Pounds 12.5m
from administrative costs to patient care over three years.
The reductions in staff in the English regions will save about Pounds 90m.
Ministers plan to replace the English regional health authorities with eight
new area offices of the NHS executive, and a maximum staffing level of 135
has been set for each of these.
Healthcare costs, Page 8
</TEXT>
