<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Construction sector chiefs expect pre-election boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government attempts to stimulate the economy in the approach to the next
general election are likely to lead to a much bigger rise in construction
output in 1996 than previously forecast, industry leaders said yesterday.
The latest an election could be held is spring 1997. Construction companies
believe ministers are determined that by then work will have started on the
Pounds 2bn Channel tunnel rail link.
Work is also likely to have started on the first generation of roads under
which contractors would receive a fee from the government to finance, build
and maintain a road for an agreed number of years. The fee would depend on
road use.
The National Council of Building Material Producers said yesterday that this
could lead to a modest increase in road construction in a potential election
year.
As a result the council, which represents companies with a combined annual
turnover of more than Pounds 30bn, has increased its forecast for
construction growth in 1996. It expects output to rise 4 per cent in the
year, compared with only 2.5 per cent when it last published forecasts four
months ago.
The biggest change is a much improved forecast for infrastructure work,
which is expected to rise 3 per cent in 1996. Previously the council
forecast a 3 per cent fall.
Cuts in public spending mean infrastructure output is expected to fall
sharply in the next two years - by 7 per cent this year and 5 per cent next
year - before increasing in 1996.
The council has not changed its forecast that total construction output will
rise 2 per cent this year and 2.5 per cent next year, although it expects
the recovery in private housing to be slightly slower than previously
forecast.
It had forecast that builders would start work on 160,000 private-sector
homes this year. It has reduced this forecast to 155,000 to take account of
a slower rate of recovery in the housing market since Easter.
</TEXT>
