<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / DTI may widen export project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry may expand the 'export promoters'
initiative which recruits private-sector executives to the DTI to help
companies win business in world markets.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said yesterday that the
DTI had reached its initial target of 100 private-sector secondees and he
was looking at proposals to seek a second wave of recruits.
Mr Heseltine said the scheme, started 18 months ago and intended to raise UK
sales in 80 of the world's most important markets, was starting to 'run into
constraints'. He believed the only option was to increase the scale of the
operation. Recruits are seconded for two years and continue to be paid by
their employers.
The DTI initiative, regarded by Mr Heseltine as an important element in his
department's efforts to forge a working partnership with industry, has
involved more than 8,000 UK companies. He said the scheme had provided
tangible results in helping companies to find new markets and to finalise
contracts.
Mr Heseltine added: 'The promoters are forging closer ties between
government and the private sector, making business more aware of the help
available from government and enabling us to discover what it requires in
return.'
He said it was impossible to quantify the benefit to the balance of trade
but he believed it could help to reduce the deficit significantly. The
initiative offered 'open-ended benefits' to UK trade which the government
was determined to exploit.
The DTI said yesterday that, in addition to the export promoters scheme, it
planned to enlist a further 70 private-sector recruits to its nationwide
chain of Business Link centres.
They will provide access for local exporting businesses to the export
promotion resources of the DTI and the Foreign Office.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
