<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Water review aims for a three-way balance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As Mr Ian Byatt, the water industry regulator, made clear yesterday, his
price review was not only about defusing the row over soaring household
water bills. He had to ensure that the water companies have enough money to
finance the huge clean-up required by EU directives and pay adequate
dividends to shareholders.
His new K-factors, limiting price increases to 1 percentage point a year
above inflation for 10 years, are supposed to strike a three-way balance
between these considerations. Judging by the mixed reaction yesterday they
were a partial success.
Consumers were disappointed that prices will still go up. Environmentalists
said there will not be enough money to clean up beaches and rivers. Some
water companies accepted the new price controls, but one will appeal. The
stock market heaved a sigh of relief and marked up shares, but that was only
because dealers had discounted them in anticipation of the worst.
The review's main outcome - a prediction that water prices will rise by just
under 1 per cent a year in real terms over the next 10 years - is certainly
a big improvement on recent increases, which have averaged 5 per cent and
caused storms of protest. But it falls short of Mr Byatt's statement last
year that consumers did not see why water bills should rise faster than
inflation.
The consumer viewpoint was summed up by the National Consumer Council, which
only a fortnight ago published a scathing attack on the returns reaped by
water company shareholders at consumers' expense. It said: 'The fact that
prices will go up less than otherwise is obviously good news. But they will
continue to rise faster than inflation.'
There is a limit, however, to how far Mr Byatt could go in limiting price
rises. Although he can shift more investment costs from consumers and to the
water companies themselves, his first statutory duty is to ensure that the
water industry can finance its environmental obligations.
But he did not satisfy the opposition parties, which accused him of being
soft on the companies - and on generous salaries for chairmen.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's spokesman on environmental protection, said the
review had failed to stop water companies loading most of the costs of
long-term investment on current consumers. He said: 'Mr Byatt has said in
the past that the water companies could borrow much more - at preferential
rates - to finance essential long-term improvements. But here he has
completely ducked the issue.'
The reaction in the water industry ranged from cautious to grudging,
although this disguised a sense of relief that the new limits are not as
tough as many had feared.
The fact that only one company - South West Water, which faces especially
large investment demand - will challenge its new price limits is probably
the most palpable evidence that Mr Byatt has presented the industry with a
price regime it can live with - and certainly an easier one than he proposed
in his opening discussions.
Mr Mike Taylor, finance director of Northumbrian Water, said: 'I think he
struck a hard bargain with everybody, but got a little soft at the end.
Mr Mike Swallow, director of the Water Companies' Association, the trade
group, said some of his members 'have come to an initial view that (the
K-factors) are tough but succeed in striking a balance between the interests
of customers and shareholders'.
This was also the view in the City, where analysts believed that the new
K-factors would not seriously inhibit the industry's financial position, or
its ability to pay sizeable real increases in annual dividends.
Mr Lakis Athanasiou, a UBS analyst, said: 'There's a price for everything.
He could have been tighter and not given problems, but you probably would
have had a few more companies going to the MMC.'
Much of the pressure of tighter controls will have to be absorbed by greater
efficiency in the water industry. So the challenge now will be on management
to meet its investment obligations, and still have enough to keep
shareholders contented. Mr Byatt thinks the industry can manage this, and
analysts calculate that there is enough fat to keep interest and dividend
cover at healthy levels.
Even so, Mr Byatt expects that the rate of return on water-company assets
will more than halve from last year's 13 per cent to about 6 per cent over
the 10 years covered. Even though Mr Byatt expects investment and other
factors to add Pounds 47 to the typical household water bill by 2005, he
expects tighter returns and operating expenditure to cut that by Pounds 24,
bringing the increase down to Pounds 23.
But although Mr Byatt stressed that 'profits will be lower' he declined to
go into any detail. The level of profit companies earned and the dividends
they paid were a matter for company boards and management. Nor was he
willing to speculate whether his K-factors would help rein in chairmen's
salaries.
MAIN POINTS
Water prices to rise by annual average of 0.9 percentage points over
inflation from 1995-2005.
Average increase in household water bills to be Pounds 23 by 200, with wide
regional variations.
Household connection costs to be Pounds 200 next year.
10-year investment programme of Pounds 24bn
Companies' rates of return to halve in 10 years
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
