<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Companies and City satisfied with outcome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was difficult for at least nine of the 10 water and sewerage companies to
hide their satisfaction yesterday at what were widely seen to be
better-than-expected average price increases in the regulator's 10-year
review.
Welsh Water had said it would accept nothing less than a K-factor of 2 to
fund capital expenditure obligations of Pounds 1bn - the K-factor is the
number of percentage points above inflation by which companies can raise
prices. But it said the outcome - a K-factor of 0.5 - was 'absolutely
wonderful'. This was in spite of a capital spending allowance only slightly
trimmed to Pounds 950m. Mr Paul Twamley, finance director, said: 'Everyone
knows this is a negotiation.'
It appears that Mr Ian Byatt, Ofwat director-general, - who repeatedly
insisted the price review process was anything but a negotiation - had been
flexible towards the end of the review. In most cases, the draft K-factor
issued to companies for comments at the end of May had been revised upwards
for the final announcement.
One water industry executive said it had been 'touch and go up to the
eleventh hour' whether his company would go to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Although the K-factors were substantially less than those companies sought a
year ago in their market plans, capital spending obligations had been reined
in more sharply than many had expected. This was because companies had been
allowed to defer spending and because estimates for costs such as population
growth had been squeezed.
Anglian Water, where prices will rise annually by 1.5 percentage points
above inflation, said Mr Byatt had 'fixed a fair balance between
shareholders and customers'. The second five years remained unacceptable,
however. 'That has got to be put right at the turn of the century,' said Mr
Alan Smith, managing director.
Although Southern and Yorkshire refused to make their views known before
considering the details, it seems South West will be the only company to
appeal Mr Byatt's decisions.
Southern, which is particularly vulnerable to the effects of the urban waste
water review, is widely seen to be one of the biggest winners from the price
review.
The biggest loser was obviously South West, where Mr Byatt's decision to
reduce the K-factor from 11.5 to 1.5 was greeted with some puzzlement in the
industry and by the City of London. 'It looks as though they have been
stitched up,' said one industry executive.
In the end, the companies and the City were more optimistic than for some
time on earnings and dividend prospects. Water shares rose strongly as a
result, largely because of what Mr Graeme Moyse of brokers Kleinwort Benson
decribed as 'gut relief' on dividend prospects.
Analysts, who had been expecting dividend growth for the sector over the
next five years of about 3 percentage points above inflation, said 4
percentage points now seemed achievable.
Shares in regional electricity companies also moved ahead as the City
considered the implications for the power sector of the water review.
The electricity regulator is due to announce later this month a review of
the regional companies' distribution businesses, which contribute the bulk
of their profits.
