<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / TGWU chief attacks 'intimidating' faction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU, Britain's largest industrial
union, has warned his union officers that the organisation faces serious
internal conflict from a group of members who he alleges are resorting to
intimidation in trying to achieve their ends with the threat of occupying
union property.
In a circular sent this month to all TGWU branch secretaries, officers and
staff, Mr Morris says the union is involved in a 'struggle for democracy and
decency'.
His unprecedented outburst follows the occupation of the union's national
computer centre in Newcastle on July 6 by Mr John Farrell, a former TGWU
trade group secretary on Merseyside, and at least 30 of his supporters.
The group was protesting over the dismissal in June of Mr Farrell on various
conduct-related grounds, which the TGWU said included abuse of dispute
benefit payments.
Mr Farrell took court action, which ultimately failed, to prevent his
dismissal - but he plans to appeal against his dismissal at the union's
biennial conference in June next year.
Last night Mr Farrell denied the charges of intimidation in the occupation
of the computer centre. 'If he (Mr Morris) believes this, why has he not
called in the police?' asked Mr Farrell.
In his circular Mr Morris says: 'A member of the union's staff was subjected
to intimidation in the course of an action which had the effect of halting
the provision of services to the union's membership. The attack disrupted
the administration of the union, resulting in delay to union benefits being
paid and payments to TGWU pensioners.'
Mr Farrell said last night that the official concerned, who had held the key
to the office, had not reported the matter to the police.
The TGWU leader has told the union's officers that the assault on the union
was 'every bit as serious as any external challenge which we have faced over
the past 15 years'.
The union's finance and general purposes committee has condemned Mr
Farrell's temporary seizure of the building.
Mr Morris has told officials that when Mr Farrell and his supporters left
the computer centre they were reported to have 'threatened that more
so-called direct occupations would follow'.
Their occupation followed a number of internal union disciplinary hearings
over Mr Farrell's case that started in February and ended on June 17 when
the union's general executive council decided to dismiss him.
In the early stages of the affair Mr Farrell sought a High Court injunction
against the TGWU, claiming the procedures for the disciplinary hearing
against him were unfair and against natural justice. The judge dismissed Mr
Farrell's case after four days. The union is now seeking to reclaim
substantial legal costs from him over the court proceedings.
Mr Morris says in his letter to TGWU officials: 'I know you will share my
determination that we cannot allow intimidation to deter us from following
our democratic rules and procedures which have served the union well for
seventy-two years.'
</TEXT>
