FT  29 JUL 94 / Receivers to Swans gloomy on rescue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The receivers to Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder facing closure, last
night voiced grave doubts about a proposal from the sole prospective bidder
for the company.
Joint receiver Mr Ed James of Price Waterhouse said outline proposals from
French-owned Soffia/CMN would need be 'significantly improved', both in
terms of the price offered and Swans' substantial continuing operating costs
pending a sale, for there to be any chance of agreement.
He said he had invited Mr Iskandar Safa, head of Soffia, parent company of
patrol boat builder Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie, to meet him
immediately, but warned the yard's future prospects were 'extremely
uncertain'.
Mr Safa has said he will not buy Swans, which runs out of work in November,
unless it has a guaranteed two-year, Pounds 50m workload. An attempt to
fulfil this by winning the refit of the landing ship Sir Bedivere failed
last week when Rosyth won the order.
A decision by the receivers to seek more work for Swans, in the hope that
Soffia would then buy it, would be a costly gamble; tendering for an MoD
ocean survey vessel, the most imminent order prospect, would cost between
Pounds 500,000 and Pounds 1m. The receivers have said there are no other
prospective buyers.
