<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Probe on coal mine deaths reports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bilsthorpe colliery tragedy of August 1993 occurred because British Coal
misunderstood or underestimated the effects of previous workings on the rock
strata at the mine, a public inquiry has found.
Three miners died at the Nottinghamshire coal mine when they were engulfed
by a fall of sandstone half a mile underground.
The accident prompted an investigation into safety at the mine by the Health
and Safety Executive, which then set up a public inquiry conducted by Sir
Bernard Crossland of Queen's University, Belfast.
The inquiry concentrated on whether the use of rock-bolting to hold up the
roof was safe.
Under this system a bolt is driven into the rock and held fast with resin.
The bolts hold steel straps which make a caged roof for the mine roadway.
At the inquiry Mr Arthur Scargill, leader of the National Union of
Mineworkers, argued that rock-bolting made an accident like the one at
Bilsthorpe almost inevitable.
Sir Bernard called the general use of rock-bolting 'well-established and
proven'.
But in his inquiry report, he questioned the sole use of rock bolts at
Bilsthorpe because the roadway where the accident took place ran alongside
an old tunnel - so-called 'skin-to-skin working'.
There had been limited experience with rock-bolting under those conditions.
Sir Bernard drew attention to the fact that the roof was solidly supported
on one side only, and that rock fractures caused by the old Bilsthorpe
workings were underestimated.
There was 'a roof deformation mechanism which was beyond the control of the
rock bolts,' his report said.
The report also said that the use of more traditional roof support methods
would not have reduced the speed of sandstone fall.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
