<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / World Trade News: Asians upset over textiles - Change in US
rules of import origin 'will disrupt trade'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Business Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Asian textiles and clothing exporters and US retailers and garment importers
are protesting at a proposed change in US rules of origin for textiles
imports which, they say, could seriously disrupt international trade and
investment.
The proposal, which has received backing in Congress, would rewrite US
customs rules by defining products' origin according to the country where
they were 'assembled', instead of where they were cut.
Hong Kong, one of the exporters which is most at risk, said yesterday that
the change conflicted with US commitments under the Uruguay Round trade
deal. It also challenged the recent agreement to phase out the Multi-Fibre
Arrangements, which restrict world textiles trade.
The Hong Kong government has joined the governments of Australia and of
members of the Association of South East Asian Nations in writing to senior
Clinton administration officials and congressional leaders to express their
concern.
They are lobbying in close co-op-eration with the US Association of
Importers of Textiles and Apparel, whose members include jeans manufacturer
Levi-Strauss, fashion house Liz Claiborne and The Limited, a leading retail
chain.
Ms Laura Jones, the association's executive director, condemned the proposal
yesterday as a protectionist measure which would raise the cost of US
textiles imports by several hundred million dollars a year.
The proposal, strongly supported by US textiles and clothing makers, has
been approved in principle by the House of Representatives' powerful ways
and means committee as part of its draft Uruguay Round implementing
legislation. The Senate finance committee is considering a similar
amendment.
Officially, the US administration has adopted a neutral stance towards these
moves. However, critics say some senior officials have appeared to indicate
support for the change.
Though the detailed effects of the proposal are hard to predict, it could
upset existing arrangements under which textiles produced in one country are
shipped to another to be made into clothing and then exported as a product
of the first country.
Opponents fear that would require exporters abruptly to switch output
between national quotas imposed under the MFA and could lead to higher
tariffs on some US imports.
Ms Jones of the US importers' association said the proposal would
particularly affect Hong Kong, which sends large amounts of textiles to be
processed in China, whose US textiles quota is already filled to capacity.
Hong Kong said that as well as threatening existing commercial arrangements,
the proposal called into question the basis of the agreement in the Uruguay
Round to phase out the MFA. It also challenged pledges by Gatt members to
refrain from new trade restrictions before the round took effect.
Comitextil, a leading organisation of European clothing and textiles
manufacturers, said the proposal could affect some of its members' exports
to the US.
However, the organisation was not protesting because the proposal would move
US rules of origin closer to those used by the EU.
Unlike the EU, the US at present uses different rules of origin for
different types of products.
The US Treasury is currently considering plans to standardise its rules,
though it is unclear how this move would fit in with the proposals in
Congress.
Gatt members also agreed as part of the Uruguay Round to discuss ways of
harmonising their definitions of rules of origin on a worldwide basis.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
