<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Seabed mining rules approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The UN General Assembly voted yesterday to amend the Law of the Sea
convention to meet industrialised countries' objections to its seabed mining
rules, Michael Littlejohns reports from New York. The treaty will come into
force in November. As a result of the changes, the US, Britain, Germany,
Japan and other industrialised states are expected to sign it today.
They claimed the original seabed mining provisions were cumbersome,
restrictive and inimical to private enterprise. Changes in the treaty apply
clear free-market principles to seabed exploitation and protect mineral
producers and investors. But the special interests of poor developing
countries are still recognised. The treaty also allows states to create a
12-mile territorial sea limit and a 200-mile exclusive economic zone. The US
and Britain are still worried by the cost of new institutions to be set up,
including an International Seabed Authority.
</TEXT>
