<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Tug-of-war over Italian PM's brother
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lawyers were yesterday involved in a tug-of-war with Milan magistrates to
prevent the imprisonment on corruption charges of Mr Paolo Berlusconi,
younger brother of the Italian prime minister, Mr Silvio Berlusconi.
Milan magistrates issued an arrest warrant for Mr Paolo Berlusconi on
Tuesday, alleging his involvement in paying bribes totalling L330m (Pounds
136,500) to members of the Guardia di Finanza, the financial police, over
tax inspections of his brother's Fininvest group.
The arrest warrant continued yesterday to cause nervousness in the financial
markets about the stability of the right-wing coalition government. The lira
was fluctuating below the psychological floor of L1,000 against the D-Mark,
but recovered slightly to L1,003 in late trading.
Anti-corruption magistrates in Milan have insisted on detention of the
42-year-old Paolo Berlusconi on the grounds that he might tamper with
evidence.
Two weeks ago the coalition introduced a decree which limited the
judiciary's powers to use preventive detention. However, the Milan
magistrates, who were then investigating the Fininvest media empire,
threatened to resign - a threat which was largely responsible for forcing
the government to withdraw the decree five days later.
Mr Paolo Berlusconi is one of four people linked with Fininvest whose arrest
has been ordered since Friday. Only one of these, Mr Salvatore Sciascia,
head of the group's tax and accounting department, has surrendered himself.
It was largely on the basis of Mr Sciascia's confessions that Mr Paolo
Berlusconi was implicated for approving the payment of money to members of
the Guardia di Finanza between 1989 and 1992.
Milan magistrates were yesterday also seeking to establish the precise
managerial role played by Mr Silvio Berlusconi while he was head of
Fininvest and before he entered politics in last January.
They are believed to be investigating ownership of the Telepiu cable
television channel. They are checking whether Mr Berlusconi had a larger
than declared stake through nominees. If this were proved, the prime
minister could risk losing his commercial television licences.
At the political level Mr Berlusconi has begun preparing to defend his role
in the growing confrontation with the judiciary which has so weakened his
government. He is scheduled to lead a parliamentary debate next Tuesday.
In the meantime, he has rejected a suggestion by Mr Gianfranco Fini, leader
of the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance, to remove from government all
those linked to Fininvest. The advice from Mr Fini, until now his most loyal
partner in the coalition, underlines how isolated Mr Berlusconi has become
over the Fininvest affair.
Reuter adds: Mr Silvio Berlusconi will present a plan today to have a
special committee oversee his businesses, according to political sources who
declined to be named.
They said the plan called for President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro and the heads
of the two houses of parliament to name the oversight committee. Managers of
Mr Berlusconi's companies would still have powers of decision, but would
need to have their actions approved by the committee.
'It's a real separation of powers. It will cut all links between Berlusconi
and his company,' one said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
