<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Economic Watch: Dutch GDP outstrips forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dutch gross domestic product rose 1.9 per cent in the first quarter of 1994
against the year-earlier period, outstripping a preliminary estimate of 1.3
per cent made in early June. The central statistical office said the upward
revision was largely due to the availability of more accurate foreign trade
figures, which showed a 7.1 per cent jump in the volume of goods and
services sold abroad in the first three months of the year. The 1.9 per cent
increase - the highest quarterly gain since a 3.3 per cent rise in the
opening period of 1992 - was also helped by a 2.5 per cent increase in
consumer spending. Purchases of new cars were particularly buoyant, rising
by about 25 per cent against the weak first quarter of 1993.
Spain's jobless total fell by nearly 30,000 in April-June, the first
seasonally adjusted quarterly growth in employment since the opening period
of 1991. The jobless total now stands at 3.7m, or 24.2 per cent of the
working population. Denmark's unemployment rate in June dropped to 12.3 per
cent of the workforce, from 12.4 per cent in May, according to figures
released yesterday. Poland's industrial output rose 9.9 per cent in the
first six months of this year compared with last year's period. Average
inflation over the six months fell to 31.3 per cent from 35.3 per cent in
the opening half of 1993.
</TEXT>
