<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / DTI will take no action against Archer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry announced last night that it would not
be taking any action against Lord Archer, former deputy chairman of the
Conservative party, after allegations that he had been involved in insider
dealing.
In a statement the DTI announced that Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, had considered a report into possible contraventions of
insider dealing legislation by Lord Archer at the time of the bid by MAI,
the entertainment and financial group, for Anglia television group in
January 1994.
The DTI said that 'on the basis of the report and departmental and other
independent legal advice' Mr Heseltine had concluded that his department
should take 'no further action against any of the parties concerned in the
investigation'.
Lord Archer - formerly Mr Jeffrey Archer - later told reporters: 'I am
grateful to have been exonerated and would like to thank so many friends,
colleagues and well-wishers for their vigorous support following disclosure
of the investigation.'
The best-selling popular fiction writer insisted throughout the DTI
investigation that he was innocent of the allegations. His wife, Mary, is a
non-executive director of Anglia TV.
Many Tory MPs believe that disclosure of the DTI inquiry into Lord Archer,
which was leaked to a newspaper, ensured he would not be given a job in last
week's government re-shuffle, although some believe a ministerial post is
still a possibility.
The DTI's subsequent decision to confirm that Lord Archer was under
investigation was unprecedented, and met strong criticism from Tory
backbenchers.
The DTI said last night that it would not be publishing the inspectors'
report into the allegations, which Mr Heseltine received on July 19. It also
said that information on the case would, as a formality, be passed to the
Stock Exchange and to the Securities and Futures Authority.
</TEXT>
