<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 94 / Watchdog curbs water charges: Ofwat chief unveils plan to
protect householders against sharp price rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, PEGGY HOLLINGER and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new price regime designed to curb recent sharp rises in household water
bills was unveiled yesterday by Mr Ian Byatt, director-general of Ofwat, the
water industry regulator.
The controls, known as K-factors, will limit future price increases to 1
percentage point a year above inflation for the next 10 years for the
average householder.
The 31 water companies in England and Wales, each of which enjoys a local
monopoly, will also be expected to finance more of their investments
themselves through greater efficiency.
Although the new K-factors were at the tougher end of industry expectations,
they were generally welcomed as fair in the industry and the City.
Most water company shares gained on the day. Only South West Water, said it
would exercise its right to appeal to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The new K-factors are weighted to give companies more rapid price increases
in the first five years, when investments are heaviest. Average prices can
rise by 1.4 percentage points over inflation up to 2000. After that, the
average increment over inflation falls to 0.4 per cent.
But there are wide variations. Southern Water, which has heavy clean-up
costs on south coast beaches, is allowed 4 percentage points falling to 3
percentage points while four companies will not be allowed any real
increases at all in the last five years. These include South West Water,
which had one of the highest Ks last time and is now to be reined in.
Consumer groups gave the review a cautious welcome because it provided the
prospect of lower price increases, although it still meant water prices
would rise ahead of inflation. But it was attacked by environmental groups
which said it would inhibit much-needed clean-ups of rivers and beaches.
Yesterday's review marks the first reshaping of price controls for the water
industry since it was privatised in 1989.
Over that period, it has provoked controversy by raising charges by more
than inflation, while paying large increases in dividends to its
shareholders and rewarding its senior executives and directors with generous
remuneration packages.
The new controls are the outcome of a three-year review of prices and costs
which was intended to correct the failures of the price controls set at
privatisation.
In determining the K-factors, Mr Byatt said he had to allow companies enough
leeway to finance the improvements required to the water infrastructure and
the clean-up of rivers and beaches. These investments, largely imposed by
European Union directives, would total Pounds 24bn over the next 10 years.
He stressed, however, that his review was not concerned with the level of
profits and salaries, which remained a matter for company managements.
Companies were generally positive. 'It is a tough K determination,' said Mr
Brian Staples, the new chief executive of North West Water, which also got a
zero K for the last five years. 'Yet it strikes about the best possible deal
for customers given the amount of capital expenditure and provides companies
with the classical management challenge.'
Labour and the Liberal Democrats attacked the review, arguing it did little
to protect the long-term interests of the consumer or to crack down on
profits made by the water companies.
Review aims for three-way balance, Page 6
Editorial Comment, Page 13
Lex, Page 14
London shares, Page 34
</TEXT>
