<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Interest rate fears depress
US stocks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks suffered a setback as strong economic data pushed bond prices down
and raised the likelihood of an early increase in interest rates, writes
Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 15.21 lower at 3,720.47, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was off 0.79 at 452.57. Volume on
the NYSE was a moderate 251m shares. In the secondary markets, the American
SE composite dipped 0.48 to 434.02, and the Nasdaq composite closed 3.53
lower at 712.13.
The Commerce Department triggered an early decline in share prices with its
announcement that orders of durable goods had jumped 1.3 per cent last
month. The reading was much stronger than analysts had expected and
reinforced the prevailing wisdom that the Federal Reserve was prepared to
tighten monetary policy for the fifth time since February.
Further evidence of a robust economy, in spite of the four previous rate
increases, sent a shiver through the bond market, where the price of the
inflation-sensitive 30-year government issue retreated by about 1/2 of a
point.
Stocks mostly followed the lead of the Treasury market, but the session was
complicated by the release of a fresh batch of corporate results. With a
tentative mood still prevailing, some good performances went unrewarded
while the share prices of under-achievers were often marked down sharply.
Among the Dow industrial components, Disney fell into the first category.
Its stock added Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 42 1/8 , a modest gain in view of
second-quarter earnings of 49 cents a share, about 3 cents above
expectations.
3M added Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 51 3/8 as investors shrugged off the
company's strong second-quarter performance.
Ford, which handily beat Wall Street's projections, fared even worse, as its
stock lost Dollars 1 to Dollars 30 1/4 amid fears that the car industry's
recovery had passed its peak.
Bethlehem Steel came under the heading of under-achiever. Its share price
dropped Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 20 3/4 after the company posted a profit of
14 cents a share, about half of what analysts had forecast.
The uncertainty over interest rates took its toll on several other stocks
sensitive to broad economic trends. Alcoa lost Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 77
7/8 and International Paper was down Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 71.
In a development unrelated to earnings news, Signet Banking climbed Dollars
2, or 7 per cent,to Dollars 39 1/4 after revealing plans to spin off its
credit card operations.
The brightest star of the session was Biogen, the biotechnology concern
whose shares are traded on the Nasdaq. The stock was swept 52 per cent
higher to Dollars 44 3/4 , a gain of Dollars 15 1/4 on the day, with some
14m shares traded. The surge followed the company's announcement that
clinical tests of a drug to treat multiple sclerosis had produced promising
results.
Meanwhile, Chiron, a rival biotech concern, had a bad day, with its share
price slumping Dollars 5 1/8 to Dollars 52 5/8 . Wertheim Schroder
downgraded the issue, citing the potential for new competition for Chiron's
multiple sclerosis treatment.
Canada
Toronto stocks fell for the third consecutive day, in moderate trading. The
TSE-300 composite index lost 15.89 points, or 0.38 per cent, to 4,134.01,
with declines outpacing advances 428 to 272.
Volume of 57.30m shares was above Tuesday's 56.13m. Trading value was
CDollars 655.0m compared with CDollars 651.0m.
Lac Minerals rose CDollars  1/8 to CDollars 14 3/8 after reporting
second-quarter net profit against a year-earlier loss. Lac also disclosed in
filings with US securities regulators that it has held third-party talks
regarding various transactions to maximize shareholder value.
Imasco said its second-quarter net rose to CDollars 128m from CDollars 95m a
year earlier, despite about CDollars 24m in pre-tax charges this year.
Imasco's shares gained CDollars  3/4 to CDollars 34 3/4 .
Mexico
Equities rose 1.66 per cent in active trading driven up by investor buying
following a decline in key interest rates and several solid first-half
company results.
The bolsa had its fifth consecutive advance on the back of a 66-basis-point
fall in the rates for 28-day Cetes, or Treasury bills, to 17.00 per cent in
yesterday's auction.
The key IPC index closed up 39.82 points at 2,433.22. At the end of 1993,
the IPC stood at 2,602.63. Volume totaled a heavy 2.05bn new pesos, on
137.5m shares traded.
</TEXT>
