<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / International Company News: High-tech groups report gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GM Hughes Electronics and Allied-Signal, two US high-technology groups,
posted higher second-quarter earnings yesterday as growing automotive and
commercial aerospace revenues offset a decline in sales of defence-related
products.
GMHE, a subsidiary of General Motors, reported a 15 per cent gain in
second-quarter profits to Dollars 267.3m, or Dollars 67 cents a share, on
revenues of Dollars 3.5bn, up from Dollars 3.3bn a year earlier. First-half
profits totalled Dollars 579.8m, against Dollars 421.3m in 1993.
It said productivity improvements and continued growth in its non-defence
businesses were behind the gains.
Revenues from GMHE's automotive electronics division rose 24.3 per cent to
Dollars 1.43bn thanks to increased production of GM vehicles, which GMHE
supplies with electronic products, and stronger international and non-GM
sales.
The company's telecommunications and space operations saw revenues climb
24.6 per cent to Dollars 548.9m, mainly due to work on government-related
satellite manufacturing programmes and a contract to supply communications
equipment to BellSouth Cellular.
GMHE's defence electronics division reported a 10.5 per cent decline in
revenues to Dollars 1.38bn, while its commercial technologies unit also saw
revenues fall, from Dollars 168m a year ago to Dollars 163.1m.
Allied-Signal reported second-quarter profits of Dollars 196m, or 69 cents a
share, up from Dollars 167m, or 59 cents, a year ago and a record for the
New Jersey-based company. The strong second quarter took first-half earnings
to a record Dollars 365m, up from Dollars 313m in 1993.
During the quarter, its sales rose 4 per cent to Dollars 3.2bn. The
company's engineered materials division led the way, reporting sales of
Dollars 88m, up from Dollars 73m a year ago. The performance of its
automotive division was also impressive. It reported a 32 per cent increase
in net income to Dollars 62m on record sales of Dollars 1.25bn.
Allied-Signal's aerospace division posted higher net income, with profits
from the unit rising 17 per cent to Dollars 61m as productivity gains helped
offset lower military spending, which kept sales flat.
</TEXT>
