<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / International Company News: Improved volumes spark 53% surge
at Du Pont
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Volume growth drove a 53 per cent jump in earnings at Du Pont, the US
chemicals group, in the second quarter, comfortably ahead of market
forecasts.
The advance was achieved despite lower prices than a year ago. Mr Edgar
Woolard, chairman, said the company expected earnings to continue to
outperform 1993 for the rest of the year.
The quarterly sales of Dollars 10.2bn were 6 per cent up on a year before,
even though prices in most areas of business were 3 per cent or more lower.
All of Du Pont's business segments recorded improvements over a year before:
The chemicals segment saw net income of Dollars 101m, up 11 per cent on the
year, despite a 5 per cent fall in selling prices.
A 61 per cent improvement in earnings from the fibres business, to Dollars
177m, was due largely to the acquisition of ICI's nylon business, which
pushed up sales by 13 per cent. Without this, sales were up 3 per cent.
The polymers business reported a 71 per cent earnings advance, to Dollars
183m, due to the divestment of some businesses over the year. Excluding the
effect of these, sales were up 13 per cent year-on-year.
After a further Dollars 47m charge to settle claims relating to the
fungicide Benlate, earnings in the diversified businesses segment rose 72
per cent to Dollars 208m.
Underlying earnings in the petroleum operations rose only marginally, to
Dollars 210m. This still marked a better experience than most other big oil
groups during the period.
Net income for the quarter of Dollars 792m, or Dollars 1.16 a share,
compared with Dollars 516m, or 76 cents the year before. First-half net
income of Dollars 1.4bn was up from Dollars 1bn.
</TEXT>
