<DATE>940728
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / International Company News: Ford returns to the black in
Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ford's European automotive operations (excluding Jaguar) achieved a Dollars
310m turnround in the second quarter with a net profit of Dollars 244m
compared with a net loss of Dollars 66m in the same period a year ago.
The financial improvement in Europe, following three successive years of
losses, reflects the gradual recovery in the west European new car market as
well as far-reaching restructuring.
Jaguar, Ford's UK luxury car subsidiary, remained in the red in the second
quarter with an unchanged operating loss of Dollars 62m. However, Ford said
Jaguar was expected to return to profit in 1995, ending six successive years
of losses.
Ford's European automotive operations suffered total losses in 1991-93 of
Dollars 3.3bn, including Jaguar, and Dollars 1.5bn excluding Jaguar.
The return to profit in Europe follows two years of retrenchment in which
the Ford of Europe workforce (excluding Jaguar) has been cut by 15.4 per
cent to 83,000 people by the end of last year from 98,100 in November 1992.
Ford said the financial recovery reflected higher sales volumes with demand
picking up in most European markets from the depth of last year's recession,
as well as cost-cutting primarily in manufacturing and purchasing.
In the first half of the year Ford of Europe (excluding Jaguar) achieved a
net profit of Dollars 353m compared with a loss of Dollars 47m in the
corresponding period a year ago.
Jaguar's operating loss in the first six months was reduced to Dollars 102m,
compared with Dollars 118m.
Ford's European automotive operations including Jaguar (operating losses and
acquisition costs) improved to a net profit of Dollars 160m in the first six
months from a deficit of Dollars 257m in the same period last year.
In the second quarter, Ford of Europe has increased its market share and has
raised production in order to build up dealer stocks in the expectation of
strong demand in the third quarter.
Ford said there had been an underlying improvement in Jaguar's operating
results following progress in lowering costs and raising product quality.
Jaguar increased its worldwide retail sales by 14 per cent in the first half
of the year to 14,800, against 13,000 with increases of 25 per cent in the
US and 16 per cent in the UK partially offset by a 37 per cent decline in
Germany.
Ford has increased its share of the western European new car market in the
first six months to 11.7 per cent from 11.5 per cent a year ago helped by
strongly rising sales of the Mondeo, which have offset a loss of market
share by the Escort and Fiesta ranges. It has gained market share in the UK,
Germany and Spain but has lost ground in France and Italy.
</TEXT>
