<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / K-factors and their knock-on effects: Water prices over the
next five years will be determined by today's announcement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The water industry regulator will today unveil the rate at which he will
allow the 31 water and sewerage companies of England and Wales to increase
prices over the next 10 years.
Most analysts are expecting Mr Ian Byatt, director-general of the Office of
Water Services (Ofwat), to aim for an average annual weighted increase,
between 1995 and 2000, of more than 1 per cent above inflation - the formula
known as the K-factor.
Such an outcome, says Mr Graeme Moyse, of stockbrokers Kleinwort Benson,
would allow the 10 water and sewerage companies to maintain dividend growth
at an attractive 3 per cent per annum above inflation for the next five
years. It is almost certain Ofwat will re-examine price increases in 1999,
rendering comments on the last five years of the period under review
virtually irrelevant.
While the K-factor has been the focus of publicity, Mr Byatt's decisions on
the amount of capital spending to sanction for each company will be equally
important. Just over a year ago, water companies submitted market plans to
the regulator showing obligations believed to total between Pounds 20bn and
Pounds 25bn for the sector as a whole. Talks between the Department of the
Environment and Ofwat are thought to have reduced the number by at least a
quarter. It will become clear today which companies are set to benefit most
from those discussions.
For individual companies, a high capital expenditure allowance would imply a
high K-factor. However, Mr Byatt has said he intends to place more of the
funding burden on the companies. So, a tough approach would be to sanction a
large amount of capital spending, but be stingy with the price increase.
Companies, already expecting flat earnings over the next five years, would
be forced to eat further into their own resources to fund the spending. Such
an approach from Ofwat would rely on harsh efficiency targets, also to be
announced today.
Those trying to determine a list of winners and losers in today's
announcement are unlikely to get much guidance from the companies or from
Ofwat.
Individual companies were informed of their own K-factors yesterday, but
they will be keenly interested to see how they have fared compared with
others in the sector before they comment. If some feel hard done by, they
have two months to appeal to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. Thus,
the uncertainty which has plagued the sector for the last year is unlikely
to evaporate overnight.
Lex, Page 18; Yorkshire Water, Page 21
