<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / Cardiff wins Pounds 200m TV component plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Japanese-German joint venture to make television components, involving a
planned investment of nearly Pounds 200m, is to be set up at Cardiff Bay. Up
to 750 jobs are expected to be created in what is potentially one of the
biggest inward investments yet in Wales.
The venture, between Nippon Electric Glass and Schott Glaswerke, will make
glass for cathode ray tubes. The first customer will be the Sony television
plant at Bridgend in south Wales, which at present imports these components.
The factory is the most important manufacturing investment yet won by the
Cardiff Bay Development Corporation, which is responsible for regenerating
2,700 acres of old docklands. Site preparation for the factory will begin
next month and production is due to start next year.
Initially, Pounds 30m will be invested and 70 people employed in grinding
and polishing panels. But the joint venture intends to develop a fully
integrated manufacturing facility for cathode ray glass over five years.
Depending on the market, the companies forecast an investment of Pounds 193m
and a workforce of up to 750 people over that period.
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, described it as 'an immense vote of
confidence in Wales by two world leaders in their field. For them to choose
south Wales over competing sites throughout Europe is further proof of our
attraction to international companies'.
NEG and Schott will receive an undisclosed amount of regional selective
assistance from the Welsh Office. The development corporation will provide
financial help, which is still being negotiated, in the construction costs
of the factory.
Sir Geoffrey Inkin, chairman of the corporation, said the announcement was
'a major industrial milestone in the regeneration of Cardiff Bay'.
Mr Michael Boyce, chief executive, said: 'I can't think of a more important
inward investment for us to attract - we have shared everyone's concern
about the weakening of Cardiff's manufacturing base.'
It is the first large deal struck by the development corporation since work
started in May, after protracted opposition, to construct a barrage across
Cardiff Bay to create a freshwater lake.
</TEXT>
