<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Here's a plot for a blockbuster novel: under the sea off the Norwegian coast
lies a graveyard for Russian nuclear submarines. The official view is that
they are safe, but the fear is that they are leaking radioactive
contamination that could destroy the world. According to True Stories
(Channel 4 at 9.30) this is exactly what is happening. Only now are the
stories of the disasters which have befallen the Soviet fleet of nuclear
submarines coming to light. They are believed to have claimed the lives of
more than 200 men, hence the title, The Widow Makers.
A bogeywoman who ended her career a much loved superstar features in Martina
 -Farewell to a Champion (BBC 1 at 10). The life of the tennis ace Martina
Navratilova is traced from childhood in Prague to emotional exit from
Wimbledon this summer as beaten finalist.
The Proms get a TV screening tonight (BBC 2 at 7.30), thanks to the
appearance of the dynamic Simon Rattle and his City of Birmingham Symphony
Orchestra. The programme ranges from Sibelius to Debussy and includes a new
work by Mark-Anthony Turnage.
