<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / Troubled health authority 'concealed information'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Debt forecasts for South Birmingham District Health Authority last year
jumped from Pounds 12m to Pounds 16m in a month because 'information had
been concealed to feed out bad news in increments', the Commons public
accounts committee said in a critical report yesterday.
It says financial controls in the troubled authority were so poor that it
failed to recover Pounds 3m owed by other health authorities. South
Birmingham, West Midlands Regional Health Authority and the government's
National Health Service Executive all shared some responsibility for failure
to address the problems, it adds.
The committee says it was not clear why a former chief executive and finance
director of the South Birmingham authority, who were 'in effect dismissed
from their posts', had subsequently been working as NHS consultants.
Mr Tom Sackville, junior health minister, acknowledged that the report
addressed 'serious matters' - but said a range of remedial actions had
already been taken.
This new criticism of poor financial controls in the NHS comes as the
government is about to announce the results of a review aimed at
streamlining central administration and reducing bureaucracy. Mrs Virginia
Bottomley, health secretary, set up the review last year to determine the
future shape of the Department of Health now that much decision-making has
been devolved to local level.
Senior staff at the department's headquarters in Whitehall and the
Leeds-based NHS Executive, which has day-to-day managerial responsibility
for the service, have been told to stand by for an announcement on the
outcome of the review today.
It is certain to lead to job losses at both locations, in addition to cuts
which are arising from amalgamations of regional health authorities.
The British Medical Association yesterday told its members not to negotiate
local pay schemes with trust hospital managements as part of its resistance
to government proposals to introduce performance-related pay for doctors. A
special national conference to protest against the plans has been called by
the BMA for August 31.
</TEXT>
