<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / Blair stands against Post Office sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, yesterday launched a campaign to keep the
Post Office in the public sector.
He said he believed it would be 'foolish and dogmatic' to privatise a
profitable and successful Post Office and urged the government to give it
more commercial freedom in the public sector.
Labour's campaign was launched amid signs that ministers doubt whether they
will succeed in getting their favoured option of a partial sell-off through
the Commons.
Seven Tory MPs have signed an early-day motion calling for the corporation
to remain nationalised but with more commercial freedom.
A senior Whitehall official said: 'Ministers are not taking anything for
granted. No one is over-confident. The government does understand the
concerns of the so-called Post Office sceptics.'
The government has published a green paper setting out three options: full
privatisation of the Royal Mail and Parcelforce, the sale of 51 per cent of
the shares in the two companies, or more commercial freedom in the public
sector.
Mr Blair said Labour's campaign was not based on ideological opposition to
privatisation. He recently called for a 'dynamic market' and his advisers do
not want to give the impression that the party is opposed to all
privatisation.
Mr Blair fears that private owners of Royal Mail would try to cut costs by
reducing its payments to Post Office branches. 'That would put at risk many
community post offices that need cross subsidies to stay open,' he said.
Mr Robin Cook, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, said he would be
travelling to many Tory marginal seats in rural areas to warn of the threat
to village post offices that rely on cross subsidies.
Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief executive, emphasised that the
government's decision to keep Post Office Counters in the public sector, but
with freedom to conduct a wider range of businesses, assured the future of
the countrywide network of 20,000 post offices.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
