<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / Eggar to quiz industry on competitiveness measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tim Eggar, the new minister for industry and energy, is to launch an
initiative to find out what crucial industrial sectors want from the
government to help them improve their competitiveness.
In his first briefing since last week's reshuffle - in which he took on the
industry portfolio at the Department of Trade and Industry in addition to
his energy responsibilities - Mr Eggar said the biggest issue for industry
was competitiveness. One of his roles would be to look at how to take the
issue forward following the publication in May by Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary, of the white paper on competitiveness.
Mr Eggar said he had asked officials to find out from industrial sectors and
sub-sectors the top three or four issues where government action could help
them.
The announcement does not amount to a change of policy by the DTI, and Mr
Eggar said he wanted industry to identify the priorities.
Mr Eggar's broader role follows the retirement of Mr Tim Sainsbury as
industry minister, and he also takes on responsibility for the Post Office.
Mr Charles Wardle, under-secretary of state for industry and energy,
supports him on all industry, energy and regional issues.
</TEXT>
