<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / Minister predicts education revolution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pupils leaving school at 16 without plans for further education and training
will soon be a thing of the past, Mr Eric Forth, the new education minister,
said yesterday, Lisa Wood writes.
Mr Forth, commenting on education participation figures which take into
account those entering post-16 education in September last year, said: 'The
last 10 years have seen a revolution in the participation of 16 to
18-year-olds in education.'
The figures show that:
80 per cent of those aged 16 are staying on in full and part-time education
 -up by more than 15 percentage points since 1984.
Nearly 73 per cent of 16-year-olds are in full-time education - up 25
percentage points since 1984.
More than 55 per cent of pupils aged 16 to 18 are in full-time education - a
rise of more than 3 percentage points since last year.
The number of full-time pupils and students aged 16 to 18 is at an all-time
high of 924,000 in spite of a decrease in the size of the age group.
