<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / High collection rate reported for council tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most local councils have achieved high collection rates for council tax, the
Audit Commission says in a report on the first year of the tax, published
today.
The local authority watchdog says that almost 93 per cent of the Pounds
7.3bn to be paid by taxpayers in 1993-94 was collected by the end of March.
Under the poll tax, councils managed to collect less than 90 per cent of the
tax in the year it was due.
Some councils have experienced problems in council-tax collection, however,
in part because of the legacy of difficulties in collecting the poll tax.
Nine had collected less than 80 per cent of the tax due, with the London
borough of Lambeth having brought in less than half.
The report says that almost Pounds 1.8bn of poll tax remained uncollected at
the end of March, a year after the tax was abolished.
There is expected to be Pounds 1.5bn outstanding by the end of next year,
much of which will have to be written off as too expensive to col-lect, the
commission believes.
According to the commission the cost of collecting poll tax arrears averages
Pounds 100 per case. But targeting recovery on the largest arrears can still
be cost-effective, the report says. People who owe Pounds 250 or more
account for more than 60 per cent of the money outstanding.
The commission says that the success of local authorities in collecting
council tax has restored the credibility of local taxation.
One in seven councils, however, had collected less than 90 per cent of the
tax due by the end of March, and no money had been collected from a fifth of
households in some authorities, largely because of poor record-keeping or
slow administration.
The 12 inner-London boroughs, which suffered some of the best organised poll
tax strikes, are among the worst performing councils. But some rural areas
such as Kerrier in Cornwall and Charnwood in Leicestershire are also among
the laggards, the commission says.
It says: 'There is only a very weak link between collection rates and the
extent of an area's deprivation.'
Collecting council tax and the uniform business rate cost local authorities
about Pounds 700m last year, the commission says. This is more than is spent
on refuse collection.
The commission says costs vary between Pounds 7 and Pounds 30 per household.
There was no correlation between cost and collection rates - one of the
highest collection rates was achieved by one of the lowest-cost authorities.
It says more needs to be done to use computer systems to improve collection
levels. Sixty per cent of councils cannot easily identify those who have
paid nothing and many fail to target persistent late payers who need firmer
action to get them to pay.
Now, the Good News: The First Year of Council Tax. HMSO. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
