FT  28 JUL 94 / Porter fails in move to make auditor quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dame Shirley Porter, former leader of Westminster City Council, has failed
in an attempt to have Mr John Magill, the district auditor, replaced before
public hearings this October.
Her move was supported by at least one of the other nine former Westminster
councillors and officials who, with Lady Porter, Mr Magill has recommended
should be surcharged a total of Pounds 21.5m.
Lady Porter applied to the Audit Commission, the local authority watchdog,
in April to have Mr Magill replaced by a new auditor. Mr Bill Phillips,
former chief executive of the council, made a similar application in the
month before but both have been rejected.
The row follows Mr Magill's preliminary findings in January that 'designated
sales' of council houses in the late 1980s were unlawful.
He ruled that the policy of removing 500 council properties a year from
public ownership was designed to increase owner-occupancy in eight marginal
wards and boost the Conservative party vote.
It was also at the price of failing to fulfil obligations to the homeless
and other priority housing groups.
In her letter of complaint to the Audit Commission Lady Porter, through her
solicitors Brecher &amp; Co, criticised Mr Magill over the press conference he
held in January.
The letter says: 'The behaviour of Mr Magill is in our view ill-judged. In
these circumstances the removal of Mr Magill is a necessary step in the
interests of justice.'
She also complained that 'the report and summary prepared by Mr Magill and
provided by him to the media go far beyond merely provisional findings'.
Mr Magill, in his submission to the Audit Commission, said: 'My note of
provisional findings and views makes abundantly clear that my findings and
views are provisional only. I retain an open mind.'
Mr Roger Rosewell, a spokesman for Lady Porter, said yesterday that it was
likely that she would personally ask Mr Magill to stand down before public
hearings start in London on October 17 or at the beginning of the hearings.
Mr Rosewell said yesterday: 'We have no confidence in his impartiality. We
have to persuade him that what he said at the press conference in January
was disgraceful.'
Mr Magill said earlier this month that he hoped that any approach to him to
disqualify himself would come before the beginning of the public hearings to
avoid inconvenience.
</TEXT>
